{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625924"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17047"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17047"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.53,0.11,0.16,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76995"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9737"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17047"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62501"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5084"},{"type":"tags","id":"5134"},{"type":"tags","id":"8511"},{"type":"tags","id":"8561"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23070"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76995"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHistamine H1 receptor antagonists are commonly prescribed medications for preventing motion sickness. Their therapeutic effect requires them to reach specific areas in the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how H1 antihistamines prevent motion sickness?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Block histamine receptors in the gastric mucosa","Block histamine receptors in brainstem motion centres","Block histamine release from brainstem neurons","Block histamine synthesis in vestibular cells","Block histamine transport across synapses"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EH1 antihistamines prevent motion sickness by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking histamine receptors in brainstem motion centres\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically the vestibular nucleus and vomiting centre. This dual action prevents vestibular stimulation from triggering the vomiting reflex during motion exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlock histamine receptors in the gastric mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E works peripherally, but the antiemetic effect requires central nervous system action.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlock histamine release from brainstem neurons\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as H1 antihistamines act as receptor antagonists and do not influence histamine release.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlock histamine synthesis in vestibular cells\u003C/strong\u003E is not the mechanism as H1 antihistamines have no effect on histamine synthesis pathways.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlock histamine transport across synapses\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as H1 antihistamines do not affect histamine transport or release.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst-generation H1 antihistamines like dimenhydrinate and promethazine are effective because they readily cross the blood-brain barrier to reach these central nervous system sites. This also explains their sedating effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["H1 antihistamines block histamine receptors in both the vestibular nucleus and vomiting centre of the brainstem.","Motion sickness involves activation of vestibular H1 receptors which stimulate the vomiting centre.","First-generation H1 antihistamines must cross the blood-brain barrier to exert their antiemetic effect."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62501"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17047"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62501"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:06:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:07:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9737"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76995"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":nul